Every large Angular app has one. It starts innocently: a few shared pipes, a button component, a utility function. Then someone adds a service because вҖңeveryone needs it.вҖқ Then a model, because вҖңitвҖҷs used in two places.вҖқ Then another service. Then a component that imports a service that imports another service, and now your SharedModule has a circular dependency with CartModule That nobody can explain.
SharedModule
в”ңв”Җв”Җ ProductService вҶҗ Used by Catalog AND Cart AND Checkout
в”ңв”Җв”Җ Product (interface) вҶҗ Used everywhere, but means different things
в”ңв”Җв”Җ UserService вҶҗ Used by Profile AND Auth AND Orders
в”ңв”Җв”Җ FormatPricePipe вҶҗ Simple utility
в”ңв”Җв”Җ ButtonComponent вҶҗ Fine to be here
в””в”Җв”Җ CartHelper вҶҗ Wait, why is Cart logic in Shared?The real problem isnвҖҷt the SharedModule itself вҖ” it's that we conflated two different things:

вҖў Genuinely shared UI primitives (buttons, inputs, pipes)

вҖў Domain concepts that happen to be referenced by multiple parts of the app
Bounded Contexts solve the second problem. They give you a principled way to decide what belongs where.

What Is a Bounded Context?
A Bounded Context is a boundary within which a particular domain model applies. Inside that boundary, every term has a precise meaning. Outside it, the same word might mean something different.
In ShopFlow, the word вҖңProductвҖқ appears in at least three contexts:
ContextWhat вҖңProductвҖқ meansKey fieldsCatalogSomething a customer browses and considersName, description, images, reviews, variants, price rangeCartA reference to what the customer intends to buyProductId, selected variant, quantity, unit price at time of addingOrdersA historical snapshot of what was purchasedName at time of purchase, price paid, SKU
If you use a single Product interface everywhere, it has to carry all these fields at once. It becomes a 25-property God interface that's used differently in each context, making it impossible to evolve any one context without affecting all the others.
A Bounded Context says: itвҖҷs okay for the same word to mean different things in different parts of the app вҖ” as long as each contextвҖҷs definition is internally consistent and the boundaries between contexts are explicit.

