в””в”Җв”Җ shared-kernel.module.tsDefining the Module Boundaries
Each bounded context module exposes only what other contexts are allowed to use вҖ” its public API:
typescript
// catalog/catalog.module.ts
@NgModule({
declarations: [
ProductCardComponent,
ProductListComponent,
ProductDetailComponent,
],
imports: [
CommonModule,
SharedKernelModule,
RouterModule.forChild(catalogRoutes),
],
exports: [
// вң… These are the public-facing components of the Catalog context
ProductCardComponent,
ProductListComponent,
// вқҢ CatalogFacade is NOT exported from the module вҖ” use DI tokens
// вқҢ Domain classes are NOT exported вҖ” they're implementation details
],
providers: [
CatalogFacade,
{ provide: PRODUCT_REPOSITORY, useClass: ProductApiRepository },
]
})
export class CatalogModule {}The CatalogFacade is injectable across the app via DI вҖ” but the domain classes (CatalogProduct, ProductVariant) should ideally not be imported directly by other contexts. Other contexts should use the IDs and communicate through events or the shared kernel.
Barrel Files as the Public API Contract
typescript
// catalog/index.ts вҶҗ The ONLY file other contexts should import from
export { CatalogModule } from './catalog.module';
export { CatalogFacade } from './application/catalog.facade';
export { ProductCardComponent } from './presentation/product-card/product-card.component';
// вқҢ Do NOT export domain classes intended to be internal:
// export { CatalogProduct } from './domain/catalog-product.entity'; // internalIf another developer tries to reach into catalog/domain/catalog-product.entity.ts directly, that's a boundary violation. The barrel file is the gatekeeper.
Enforcing Boundaries with ESLint
For standard Angular CLI projects without Nx, you can use eslint-plugin-boundaries:
bash
npm install --save-dev eslint-plugin-boundariesjavascript
// .eslintrc.js
module.exports = {
plugins: ['boundaries'],
settings: {
'boundaries/elements': [
{ type: 'shared-kernel', pattern: 'src/app/shared-kernel/*' },
{ type: 'catalog', pattern: 'src/app/catalog/*' },
{ type: 'cart', pattern: 'src/app/cart/*' },
{ type: 'checkout', pattern: 'src/app/checkout/*' },
{ type: 'orders', pattern: 'src/app/orders/*' },
]
},
rules: {
'boundaries/element-types': ['error', {
default: 'disallow',
rules: [
// Any context can import from shared-kernel
{ from: '*', allow: ['shared-kernel'] },
// Cart can reference Catalog (to show product names in cart)
// but only through the Catalog's public facade, not domain internals
{ from: 'cart', allow: ['catalog'] },
// Checkout can reference Cart
{ from: 'checkout', allow: ['cart', 'catalog'] },
// Orders is standalone вҖ” references shared-kernel only
{ from: 'orders', allow: ['shared-kernel'] },
]
}]
}
};For Nx projects, use @nx/enforce-module-boundaries in project tags вҖ” it's even more powerful.

Cross-Context Communication: How Contexts Talk to Each Other
Bounded contexts should not directly import each otherвҖҷs domain models. But they still need to communicate. Here are the three patterns for ShopFlow:
Pattern 1: Shared IDs (The Most Common)
The Cart context needs to display a product name. It has a ProductId from the CartProductRef. To get the full details, it uses the CatalogFacade:
typescript
// cart/application/cart.facade.ts
@Injectable({ providedIn: 'root' })
export class CartFacade {
constructor(
private store: Store,
private catalogFacade: CatalogFacade, // вң… Facade-to-facade, not domain-to-domain
) {} // When displaying cart items, enrich them with catalog data if needed
getCartItemsWithDetails(): Observable<CartItemViewModel[]> {
return this.store.select(selectCartItems).pipe(
switchMap(cartItems => {
const productIds = cartItems.map(item => item.productRef.productId);
return this.catalogFacade.getProductsByIds(productIds).pipe(
map(products => cartItems.map(item => ({
...item,
currentCatalogPrice: products
.find(p => p.id.equals(item.productRef.productId))
?.lowestPrice
})))
);
})
);
}
}Pattern 2: Domain Events (Covered in Article 7)
When checkout completes, the Cart context publishes a CartCheckedOut event. The Orders context subscribes to this event and creates an order. Neither context imports the other's domain model.
Pattern 3: Shared Kernel Types
Both Cart and Catalog use ProductId from the shared kernel. The ID is the bridge вҖ” the Cart doesn't need to
